## PART 3: TP6 - pfSense Port Blocking (HTTP Port 80)

### Scenario
Block HTTP (port 80) but allow HTTPS (port 443)
- Forces users to secure websites
- Prevents unencrypted web traffic

### How It Works
```
HTTP  (port 80)  → BLOCKED by firewall rule
HTTPS (port 443) → ALLOWED (no rule blocks it)
```

### Step 1: Access pfSense

```
pfSense Dashboard:
Firewall → Rules → LAN
```

### Step 2: Create Port Blocking Rule

**Why:** Block specific port, not all traffic to a host

```
Click "Add" button (up arrow)
```

**Configure Rule:**
```
Action: Reject (tell sender connection refused)
Interface: LAN
Address Family: IPv4
Protocol: TCP/UDP
```

**Source:**
```
Source: any (all computers)
```

**Destination:**
```
Destination: any (any destination)
Destination Port Range: HTTP (80)
  (This is pre-defined port in dropdown)
```

**Description:**
```
Description: Rule for Rejecting any website using http (80) port
```

**Save:**
```
Click "Save" → Click "Apply Changes"
```

### Step 3: Test HTTP Blocking

**Before Rule:**
```
Web Server Browser:
Type: http://certifiedhacker.com/
Result: Website loads ✓
```

**After Rule:**
```
Web Server Browser:
Type: http://certifiedhacker.com/
Result: "This site can't be reached" ✗
(ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED)
```

**Why Reject vs Block:**
- **Block:** Silently drops packets (slower timeout)
- **Reject:** Immediately sends "connection refused" (faster user feedback)

