## CRITICAL CONCEPTS TO REMEMBER

### 1. OSI Layer Differences
```
TP4 (Host Firewall): Layer 4 (Transport) + Application Layer
  - Blocks per-application, per-port
  
TP5 & TP6 (Network Firewall): Layer 3-4 (Network/Transport)
  - Blocks per-IP, per-domain, per-port network-wide
```

### 2. Rule Processing Order
```
Rules are processed TOP-TO-BOTTOM
First matching rule wins

Example:
Rule 1: Block all HTTP
Rule 2: Allow HTTP to 10.10.1.100
→ Result: ALL HTTP blocked (Rule 1 matches first)

Correct order:
Rule 1: Allow HTTP to 10.10.1.100
Rule 2: Block all HTTP
→ Result: 10.10.1.100 gets HTTP, others blocked
```

### 3. Stateful Firewalls
```
Modern firewalls remember connections:
- Outgoing: 10.10.1.11 → 84.53.185.208:80
- Firewall allows return traffic automatically
- Even if "no inbound rule" exists

Old stateless: Would need explicit rules for both directions
```

### 4. Default Policy
```
Windows Firewall Default: DENY incoming, ALLOW outgoing
pfSense Default: Configurable (usually DENY incoming)

Security principle: "Default Deny" = safer than "Default Allow"
```

